  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT147-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ pirintaviṭattuk kaṉāk kaṇṭu colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered at the sight of a dream when HE was separated [from her].</p>
          </div>


        <div xml:id="KT147">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                vēṉiṟ pātirik kūṉmala raṉṉa</l>
<l>                mayirō ṭoḻukiya vaṅkaluḻ māmai</l>
<l>                nuṇpūṇ maṭantaiyait tantōy pōla</l>
<l>                viṉṟuyi leṭupputi kaṉavē</l>
<l>                yeḷḷā ramma tuṇaippirin tōrē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l>O dream, you arouse [me] from sweet sleep,</l>
           <l rend="indent2">as if you had brought<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tantōy pōla</term>: what is the relation of this construction of a finite verb plus the infinitive <term xml:lang="ta">pōla</term> to that of double finite verb as in KT 103.6: <term xml:lang="ta">vāḻēṉ pōlvaṉ</term>?</note> the girl with fine ornaments,</l>
           <l rend="indent">of beautiful, [now] dimming darkness that was grown</l>
           <l rend="indent4">with a line of body-hair,</l>
           <l rend="indent">like on the curved blossom of the trumpet flower tree in summer.<note place="foot">This comparison seems to refer to a peculiar kind of plant the flowers of which have fur reminiscent of  body-hair.</note></l>
           <l>They won't censure [you], alas,</l>
           <l rend="indent3">those who are separated from [their] mates.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
